.breadcrumbs
  %ol
    %li= link_to 'GOV.UK elements', elements_index_path
    %li{ "aria-current": "page"} Buttons

%h1.heading-xlarge
  %span.heading-secondary GOV.UK elements
  Buttons

%p.lede.text Use buttons to move though a transaction, aim to use only one button per page.

%h2.heading-small.heading-contents Contents:
.grid-row
  .column-two-thirds
    %ul.list.list-contents
      %li=link_to 'Button text', '#button-text'
      %li=link_to 'Start now button', '#button-start-now'
      %li=link_to 'Button alignment', '#button-alignment'
      %li=link_to 'Disabled buttons', '#button-disabled'
      %li=link_to 'Creating buttons', '#creating-buttons'

%h3.heading-medium{ id: 'button-text'} Button text
%p.text Button text should be short and describe the action the button performs.

.example
  =submit_tag 'Save and continue', class: 'button'

%pre
  %code.language-haml
    :preserve
      =submit_tag 'Save and continue', class: 'button'

%h3.heading-medium{ id: 'button-start-now'} Start now button
%p.text Launch your service with a Start now button.

.example
  =link_to 'Start now', '#', class: 'button button-start'

%pre
  %code.language-haml
    :preserve
      =link_to 'Start now', '#', class: 'button button-start'

%h3.heading-medium{ id: 'button-alignment'} Button alignment
%p.text Align the primary action button to the left edge of your form, in the user’s line of sight.

.example.example-button
  =form_tag '/' do
    .form-group
      =label_tag nil,'Email address', class: 'form-label', for: 'form-email-address-1'
      =text_field_tag 'form-email-address-1', nil, class: 'form-control'
    .form-group
      =button_tag 'Save and continue', class: 'button'

%h3.heading-medium{ id: 'button-disabled'} Disabled buttons
%ul.list.list-bullet.text
  %li don’t disable buttons, unless there’s a good reason to
  %li if you have to disable buttons, make sure they look like you can’t click them (use 50% opacity)
  %li an example of a useful disabled option is a calendar with greyed out days where no bookings are available
  %li provide another way for the user to continue, add an error message or text to explain why the button is disabled

.example
  =button_tag 'Disabled primary button', class: 'button', disabled: 'disabled'

%pre
  %code.language-haml
    :preserve
      =button_tag 'Disabled primary button', class: 'button', disabled: 'disabled'

%h3.heading-medium{ id: 'creating-buttons' } Creating buttons
%p.text Use the GOV.UK Sass button mixin &ndash; find this in the GOV.UK frontend toolkit <a href="https://github.com/alphagov/govuk_frontend_toolkit/blob/master/stylesheets/design-patterns/_buttons.scss" rel="external">buttons.scss</a> file.

.example.example-button
  .grid-row
    .column-one-third
      =button_tag 'Save and continue', class: 'button'
    .column-one-third
      .swatch-wrapper
        %h4.heading-small Button
        .swatch.swatch-button-colour
        %ul
          %li
            %b #00823B
          %li $button-colour
    .column-one-third
      .swatch-wrapper
        %h4.heading-small Focus
        .swatch.swatch-yellow
        %ul
          %li
            %b #FFBF47
          %li $focus-colour

%p <a href="https://designpatterns.hackpad.com/Navigation-buttons-continue-next-previous-zoP1sKiW3y4" rel="external">Discuss navigation buttons on the design patterns Hackpad</a>
